<p><strong>Talpidae (<em>Neurotrichus gibbsii</em>)</strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Talpidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Neurotrichus gibbsii</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong>Shrew-Mole<br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p>The shew-mole has black or blue-black fur. They lack external ears, have small eyes, and a flattened elongated nose. Their front feet are broadened to assist in digging. They weight between 8-15 grams and are between 3.94 and 5.12 inches long  〔<a href="http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/accounts/Neurotrichus_gibbsii/" target="_blank">ADW</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>Unlike most moles the shrew-mole spends a significant portion of its time above ground, although it does dig, hunt, and sleep within its tunnels. Shrew-moles are also known to be good climbers and swimmers. The shrew-moles diet consist of earthworms, insect larvae, snails, slugs, seeds, and other invertebrates. It is active both at night and during the day 〔<a href="http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/accounts/Neurotrichus_gibbsii/">ADW</a>〕.</p>
